    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_185228565" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/185228565" />
    <a title="Andrea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/261654-andrea"><img alt="Andrea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577647049p2/261654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/185228565?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrea" href="/user/show/261654-andrea">Andrea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer185228565" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13769377287536088625">This book is very difficult to read -- which may seem like an obvious statement -- but I did not expect to personally have such a hard time reading it, as I usually do not have trouble reading hard topics. I (cried but) breezed right through Room, The Lovely Bones, Diary of Anne Frank, and The Book Thief, and I expected to do the same with Jaycee&apos;s memoir. But this was the first time I actually had to put a book down and leave it for a while because I felt physically ill after reading certain ch</span>
  <span id="freeText13769377287536088625" style="display:none">This book is very difficult to read -- which may seem like an obvious statement -- but I did not expect to personally have such a hard time reading it, as I usually do not have trouble reading hard topics. I (cried but) breezed right through Room, The Lovely Bones, Diary of Anne Frank, and The Book Thief, and I expected to do the same with Jaycee's memoir. But this was the first time I actually had to put a book down and leave it for a while because I felt physically ill after reading certain chapters. I do feel this is an important book for people to read and certainly compelling, but I give you this forewarning so you know -- the abuse she suffers is perhaps even worse than you are expecting. Certain people with sensitivities to difficult topics probably should not read this book. The descriptions of sexual abuse are not overly-gratuitous -- Jaycee writes in a very simple yet straightforward manner -- but she does give details and and it is these simple descriptions that will haunt you. I think that is what makes her memoir so moving: she does not *need* to be a gifted writer to move her readers; she does not need smooth prose or poetic language. Her story is *that* heartbreaking all on its own, just in the simple, straight-forward details of her day-to-day living in her captor's hell. <br /><br />Jaycee's memoir reads a lot like a diary (and she does include several pages of the journal she kept while in captivity): she writes as she remembers it, from the perspective of a confused &amp; terrified 11-year old. At the end of most chapters, she includes a "Reflections" section where she provides more insight and analysis of what she went through. You can see the work of her therapy here and just how far she has come in the two years since her rescue, and perhaps starting to make meaning out of her experience and make sense of it all.<br /><br />Perhaps what is most impressive -- besides the fact that she survived -- is how she does not harbor any hate, resentment or regret. Her story is truly a testament to living life in the now, living life to its fullest, and not taking any moments for granted. Her story is also a testament to the human spirit and just how much one person can endure and still triumph in the end. <br /><br />She is quite simply and unbelievably REMARKABLE.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13769377287536088625" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

